	     "Today I can announce we have offered Nigeria
further assistance in terms of surveillance aircraft, a military team to embed
with the Nigerian army in their HQ and a team to work with US experts to
analyse information on the girls' location," he told parliament. The ministry of defence clarified that one Sentinel plane
would be sent. Specialist teams from the US, Britain, France and Israel
have been sent to help in the search operation, which Nigeria's military has
said is concentrated on the Sambisa forest area of Borno state. Britain last week sent a team of experts to Nigeria
including officials from the ministry of defence. Cameron's spokesperson said
on Monday they had met Nigerian President Goodluck Jonathan. US surveillance planes have been scouring a vast swathe
of northern Nigeria looking for the girls. Boko Haram this week released a video of more than one
hundred of the girls, saying they had converted to Islam. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  